# Trivy CVE allowlist — keep tight, document every entry.
#
# Each block follows the same pattern : the CVE id, the *binary* it
# affects in our image, the reason we can't fix it at our layer, and
# what we'd track to remove the exception later.
#
# Rule of thumb : only ignore CVEs in code we vendor through a
# third-party (Chrome via puppeteer, browser engines, etc.). Anything
# in our own dependency tree gets patched via `pnpm.overrides` instead.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Go stdlib CVEs inside puppeteer's chrome-headless-shell
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# `puppeteer` (api dep, used by the Library module's Amazon book
# lookup) downloads Chrome + chrome-headless-shell at postinstall.
# Those binaries embed Go helpers (crash handler, telemetry shims) and
# Trivy decompiles them to flag the Go stdlib version. We can't bump
# Google's vendored Go without rebuilding Chrome ourselves — that's
# upstream's problem. Track on each puppeteer bump : if the next
# puppeteer release ships a Chrome with newer Go, these can drop.
#
# Reviewed for blast radius : the Go binaries only run when the api
# spawns chrome-headless-shell for an Amazon scrape. They don't sit on
# the request path and they don't terminate TLS. The CVE titles below
# are TLS-cert-validation / RegexDoS / archive-parser issues — none
# actionable through our HTTP surface.

# CVE-2025-68121 — crypto/tls: incorrect cert validation on session
# resumption. CRITICAL. Patched in Go 1.24.13.
CVE-2025-68121

# CVE-2025-58183 — archive/tar: unbounded allocation when parsing
# malformed GNU headers. HIGH. Patched in Go 1.24.8.
CVE-2025-58183

# CVE-2025-61726, CVE-2025-61728, CVE-2025-61729 — Go runtime/stdlib
# DoS surfaces. HIGH.
CVE-2025-61726
CVE-2025-61728
CVE-2025-61729

# CVE-2026-25679 — Go stdlib. HIGH.
CVE-2026-25679

# CVE-2026-32280, CVE-2026-32281, CVE-2026-32283 — crypto/x509,
# crypto/tls: DoS via crafted cert chains / TLS 1.3 keys. HIGH.
CVE-2026-32280
CVE-2026-32281
CVE-2026-32283

# CVE-2026-33811, CVE-2026-33814 — Go stdlib. HIGH.
CVE-2026-33811
CVE-2026-33814

# CVE-2026-39820, CVE-2026-39836 — Go stdlib. HIGH.
CVE-2026-39820
CVE-2026-39836

# CVE-2026-42499 — Go stdlib. HIGH.
CVE-2026-42499

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# picomatch CVE-2026-33671 inside pnpm's bundled distribution
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Our own dependency tree pins `picomatch ≥ 4.0.4` via
# `pnpm.overrides`. But the pnpm binary itself (resolved by
# `corepack enable`) ships a vendored picomatch 4.0.3 inside
# `/root/.cache/node/corepack/.../pnpm/<v>/dist/node_modules/picomatch`.
# Trivy decompiles the tarball and flags that copy. We can't
# replace it without unrolling corepack — pnpm needs the tarball
# to function.
#
# Blast radius : pnpm runs at container start (`db:migrate &&
# start`) over our own lockfile, never against attacker-controlled
# globs. The CVE (RegexDoS via crafted extglob patterns) is
# unreachable through our HTTP surface.
#
# Drop criterion : when pnpm vendors picomatch ≥ 4.0.4 in a
# corepack-distributed release. Track on each pnpm bump in
# `package.json` → `packageManager`.
CVE-2026-33671

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# vitest GHSA-5xrq-8626-4rwp inside the api image's node_modules
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# `vitest` lives in `devDependencies` but the api Dockerfile installs
# them with `--prod=false` because the runtime needs `tsx` (TypeScript
# loader for the migrate + start commands). Trivy then scans the full
# tree and flags vitest < 4.1.0.
#
# The advisory text (https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-5xrq-8626-4rwp) :
#   « When the Vitest UI server is listening, arbitrary file can be
#     read and executed. »
#
# Vitest UI is a feature spun up only when the binary is invoked with
# `vitest --ui`. Nodea never does : the CI workflow runs `vitest run`
# (CLI, no UI), no dev script in the monorepo references `--ui`, and
# the api container starts with `pnpm db:migrate:docker && pnpm
# start:docker` — no `vitest` invocation at all on the production
# request path. The UI server's code sits dormant inside `node_modules`
# and never binds to any port. Same logic as the `pnpm.auditConfig.
# ignoreGhsas` entry in the root `package.json` (which mutes the same
# advisory at audit time).
#
# Drop criterion : when we successfully complete the Vitest 4 migration
# (see PR / issue for the failed attempt's history — Vitest 4's module
# graph behaviour broke the api suite's OPAQUE round-trip).
GHSA-5xrq-8626-4rwp
